{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/adapters/process_backend.rs:412-418`, `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1058-1067`, and `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1513-1518` only kill the immediate child PID when a timeout fires. That does not kill the child's subprocess tree, so a wrapper shell or CLI that forks can leave grandchildren running after the invocation returns `Timeout`. This means the hard-timeout path still leaks backend processes/resources and does not fully satisfy the requirement that hanging backend invocations be killed. Start the backend in its own process group/job and terminate the whole group on timeout/cancel.","rationale":"Direct child SIGKILL is not sufficient for real CLI wrappers; timed-out runs can still leave orphaned backend processes behind."},{"body":"`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:4472-4481` persists the run as `Running`, then `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:4563-4641` records `stage_failed` and sleeps for backoff without any further snapshot update. If the worker is killed or the host restarts during that new 5-60s backoff window, the project is stranded in a `Running` snapshot even though no process is active, and `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:1147-1169` makes `run resume` refuse to recover it. Persist a resumable state before sleeping, or allow resume to recover stale `Running` snapshots after a retryable failure.","rationale":"The new backoff window introduces a real crash-recovery gap: a failure during sleep leaves the run non-resumable through the normal path."}],"summary":"Reviewed the retry-hardening changes in `process_backend.rs`, `retry_policy.rs`, and the workflow engine, and ran targeted unit tests for the touched areas. I found two robustness issues: timeout cleanup still only kills the direct child process, and the new retry backoff window is not durably represented in snapshot state, so a crash during sleep can strand a run in non-resumable `Running` state."}